Date:         Thu, 18 Jul 1996 23:34:12 -0800
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         Byron Massey <Byron.Massey@THEGATE.HOTLIN.FIDONET.ORG>
Organization: Fidonet: The Computer Hotline! BBS
Subject:      Card rulings and Proteus

Greetings,

My name is Byron and I have been a big Netrunner fan ever since I decided not
to play the same 3 Magic decks any more. I love the variety, strategy, and
utility of the Netrunner cards. I don't have a huge collection, but I think the
Wizards did a great job of making nearly every card really useful (there are a
*few* exceptions).

My first question is to Sparky. I read your post where you ask for patience in
regards to Joan of Arc/Misc. for Sale and also the recent question about the
Arasaka Portable Prototype/Shell Traders. One of your main points was that you
didn't want to make a ruling that only fouled up other cards later on. That's a
great idea, I agree, patience is always important (especially as the Runner),
but I have been trying to think of what problems these rulings could cause for
a while now, and I haven't been able to come up with anything.

I mean, if you just put out official WOTC ruling that said "Page 13 of  your
rulebook is correct. Cards *must* remain in the trash to generate bits for the
Misc. for Sale prep.", what other cards/combos would be affected? I can't
figure any out.

If the official WOTC ruling was "Shell Traders is not misprinted. You really do
install Arasaka Portable Protoype at *no cost*." would any other cards be
affected? Would that unbalance the game in some subtle way?

My final question is about the ICE card Ball and Chain. This seemed like a
really cool card, one I used a lot, when I played with it using the *common
sense* interpretation of how it worked. But when Rob Leachman told me how WOTC
wanted it to work, it vanished from my deck (and everyone else I have ever
played) and has never returned. What problems are being avoided by playing Ball
and Chain in this strange way (letting the runner see the next ICE before
deciding whether or not to pay for the Ball and Chain)? I hope it avoids some
terrible problem, because this ruling has turned this card into notepaper.

I guess I'm just saying I could go along with these rulings if someone at WOTC
would just post something explaining what problems are being avoided by keeping
these apparently contradictory rules.

I also think v2.0 definitely needs to reword cards like Cinderella ("this
damage cannot be prevented") and Arasaka Portable Prototype ("pay one agenda
point in addition to any other costs") and Shell Traders ("install, at no
cost"), so that two cards that are directly conflicting will have some way of
being resolved without an FAQ.

As for Proteus, I agree with the person that was concerned about the release
coming too early. I have had difficulty getting people interested in Netrunner
in my area, and adding an expansion with new victory conditions is only going
to make the situation worse. Magic is a juggernaut, but WOTC is the only entity
with the power to get people to switch over to their new, *infinitely better
built* card game. Until that effort is made, I fear Proteus could be the next
Dark Sovereigns (sp?). I think an expansion should be postponed for a couple
more months, after organized (and hopefully rated) tournaments become more than
4-8 person events. And introducing new victory conditions seems like a really
bad idea - WOTC has done such a good job with this game so far, can't they find
a way to incorporate the new card ideas into the existing rules structure (like
poison counters in Magic)?

Well, that's all for now.

-Byron
Byron.Massey@TheGate.hotlin.fidonet.org

P.S. He laughed at my use of Dr. Dreff - until he was flatlined by the surprise
Liche! :)

"The Doctor is *in*!"



