Date:         Sun, 21 Jul 1996 06:45:56 -0600
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         Greg Dglas Teed <ac419@SFN.SASKATOON.SK.CA>
Subject:      Re: Chicago Branch
In-Reply-To:  <31F279CA.645@dial.pipex.com>

On Sun, 21 Jul 1996, Ian Petchey wrote:

> Chicago Branch  2
> A,3:Add two advancement counters to an installed card that can be
> advanced.
>
> There has been a great deal of discussion on this list about corp speed
> decks.  This particular card does not seem to have had a look in.  O.K it
> is easy to trash (1) and is more expensive than say Systematic Layoffs,
> but if you can defend it and get some bit creation going then you can
> zoom though your agendas with this baby.
> Agree?  Disagree?

   My experience with Chicago Branch is that it seems to run contrary to
speed, mainly because you have to invest actions and resources
protecting its vulnerable hide. When I first saw it, I was pretty
impressed, being inclined towards permanent advantages instead of
fleeting ones. If someone were to write about the "mindblocks of
Netrunner," this would be one of them, I think. I still play Chicago
Branch, but mostly because others still see it as powerful and will focus
their attention on it instead of the real business at critical times.
When they stop being distracted by it, then I'll probably stop playing it.

   Usually, by the time I see a Chicago Branch, I already have an
Executive Extraction down and scoring takes three actions (including the
installation) anyway.

   Another problem I have with Chicago Branch is its trash cost. In the
beginning of the game, a runner can usually get a turn running R&D before
I can get the bits to rez the initial ice. I want the runner to be
stopped by whatever they access during those early runs. Chicago Branch
won't do it; it just gets trashed and the runner runs again. However, a
Systematic Layoffs will stop the runner, generally.

   I also find on those occasions where the game reaches the stage where
the runner can run fairly frequently that Systematic Layoffs is of much
greater use than Chicago Branch for two reasons:

 1. Chicago Branch is usually gone by this point, its advantage lost as
well. Systematic Layoffs is still there waiting to be taken advantage of,
and;

 2. A Systematic Layoffs is not trashable, meaning that if it's in your
hand, it's just waiting to be selected by the runner (after a run on HQ)
who can then scowl at it menacingly, but that's all. :) It reduces the
probability of something interesting being picked...

   Comments? Derisions? Deleted Expletives? Death threats?

- dglas ("Gimme dat!" - after a runner accesses Systematic Layoffs...)

**************** Greg D. Teed (ac419@sfn.saskatoon.sk.ca) ******************
