Date:         Sun, 21 Jul 1996 11:10:43 PDT
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         Bill Ingram <bing@ITS.BLDRDOC.GOV>
Subject:      Re: JOA/MFS - unfortunately it rules

--- On Sun, 21 Jul 1996 00:32:07 +0800  Patzer <med20095@THE_TRUTH_IS_OUT_THERE.WIZARDS.COM>

wrote:

>SUMMARY: at the higher levels (i.e. too much money to spend),
>Corp vs. Runner is 50/50 which is pretty cool since it makes netrunner more
>balanced and fun.

Ok, so here we are 6 weeks after the release of the game.  And where are
we?

Corp players quickly recognized the power of Speed Advancement decks.  A
few others built Tag and Bag decks.  None of the decks were tuned very
much, but won 70% or more games in the first 2 or so weeks.  The decks
are not very clever, interesting or fun.

Then, a bunch of Runner decks, that were highly tuned, began showing
up and brought the Corp percentage down to about 60%.  Most of these
decks were still "normal" deecks (i.e., non-degenerate). That was good.

Then, the Corp decks started tuning their decks and brought the percentage
back to about 70%.

The Runners responded by finding a degenerate combo...the MFS/JoA.
Personally, I think the combination can't possibly work (Card A
says, "Trash X to gain 3 bits" and Card B says, "Prevent Card A from
being trashed."  It's pretty obvious to anyone that you can't collect
3 bits when you use both cards together. Oh well.)  Anyway, the official
word is that the combo works.  So, every Runner that wants to win has
to build a MFS/JoA deck.  And that deck is now winning most of its games.
IMHO, it's not very clever, interesting, or fun.

So, we finally have a kind of a balance.  If you are the Corp, you
must play Speed Advancement or Tag and Bag.  If you play Runner, you
must play JoA/MFS.  If you play anything less than these, you will
loose decisively.

>all IMHO, I'm not trying to offend anyone. If you really have a great deck
>without JOA/MFS, cool. I wouldn't mind making one w/o JOA/MFS cos' I would
>like to see it banned :)

Kinda.  If you ban the MFS/JoA combo (or just declare that it obviously
doesn't work), the Speed Advancement decks will rule.  So, you gotta
restrict the fast advancement cards.  But then, the Tag and Bag decks will
rule.  I'm not sure what you can restrict to slow those decks down.

Of course, WotC is very possesive about their game, so don't expect them
to ban or restrict cards or to change the rules any time soon.

Anyway, my original predictions for the game are still on track.  The
game has turned into a battle of degenerate and not-very-fun decks.
In six months (five now) it will dwindle down to just the hard-core
players with degenerate decks who can't find anyone (except other
degenerate decks) to play (much like what happened to Star Trek,
Star Wars, INWO, etc.).

"Of course," you say, "degenerateness is a fact of life in MtG and almost
every other CCG."  True.  But, it happened to NetRunner a lot faster than
it happened to most other CCGs.  And, most folks claim that degenerate
decks are actually the biggest problem with MtG and other CCGs.  It just
seems frustrating that WotC would release a new game that is an obvious
breeding pit for degenerateness.

