Date:         Sun, 21 Jul 1996 13:20:01 -0700
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         "David R. Liu" <davidliu@VIOLET.BERKELEY.EDU>
Subject:      Re: NETRUNNER-L Digest - 20 Jul 1996 to 21 Jul 1996

Bill "I love Netrunner" Ingram wrote:

===============
Anyway, my original predictions for the game are still on track.  The
game has turned into a battle of degenerate and not-very-fun decks.
In six months (five now) it will dwindle down to just the hard-core
players with degenerate decks who can't find anyone (except other
degenerate decks) to play (much like what happened to Star Trek,
Star Wars, INWO, etc.).

"Of course," you say, "degenerateness is a fact of life in MtG and almost
every other CCG."  True.  But, it happened to NetRunner a lot faster than
it happened to most other CCGs.  And, most folks claim that degenerate
decks are actually the biggest problem with MtG and other CCGs.  It just
seems frustrating that WotC would release a new game that is an obvious
breeding pit for degenerateness.
=============

Your original predictions???  First, you are way off base with your
predicitions, and second-- who cares how clairvoyant you (think) you are?

Your analysis of "degeneracy" is very superficial.  There are lots of
ways to beat corp speed decks (mostly coming from the WAY the runner
plays, not the cards he uses-- as it should be in a great game),
and no need to restrict fast advancement cards.  Further, the
JOA/MFS combo is also not invulnerable, since setting it up requires
the runner to divert valuable actions (time) towards establishment and
drawing the necessary cards instead of running.  This is very often
a mistake against a good speed corp deck.

Play some more before you jump to such conclusions.

Also, I though in your last inflammatory post you wrote off Netrunner...
are you still playing this great game?

Run rabbit run,
David
