So, Terje... (may i call you Terje ?)

>If he would come up with at least a half decent reson for why
>the combo shold work according to the current rules, I might shut up.
>If know how the Netreps from WotC are thinking and resoning to reach
>this conclusion, I might learn somthing about how also other cards
>and combos are to be interpreted. Until the opposite is proven,
>I will assume that there is some consistent logic behind the
>rulings.

It has been explained here more than once, and by Sparky "entre autres"
(terrible this loss of memory when i can't remember my proper english).
There is a rule that says: "If you can't meet up all the effects on a
card, you do all the effects you can, and forget those you can't"
So, when you play MFS then JOA, you play all the effects of MFS you can
("trash the programs i can't, get the bits i can") and forget those
you can't because they were prevented.
It's like if you have a card that says "Take 2 brain damage and win the
game" if you have a force shield in play. The 2 brain damages are not
done as they are prevented but you still win the game, ok ?

This is how it works, rules are consistent and they are clear. Some
people here don't want to understand them, because they think the
combo is too powerful. Maybe it is, but that doesn't mean the rules
are being broken.

>It is not my intention to antigonize Sparky or R&D, even if I may have
>a bit sharp in my statments. They have designed a grat game.
>Hipp hurray for that.

Well, Kewl. I agree with you on this point.

