Date:         Mon, 22 Jul 1996 08:43:38 -0400
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         "LEONARD D. BLADO" <BLADOLE@HSDWL.UTC.COM>
Subject:      Recapping the past month...

        Alright... for those of you who have been on your annual vacation
in Borneo for the past month, I'll try and sum up what we've been talking
about:

        1) JOA/MFS is a horrible ruling since the card text obviously
implies that you have to actually trash the cards in order to get the
bits.  Anything else is illogical.

        2) JOA/MFS is a fine ruling since the card text obviously
implies that both effects are independant, and you get the bits
irrelevant of whether or not the cards actually hit the trash.  Anything
else is illogical.

        3) JOA/MFS is currently deemed legal by WotC.

-Len Blado
I could sum up all the rip-offs of Stephane's tag line here if I wanted to.
=========================================================================
Date:         Mon, 22 Jul 1996 08:53:18 -0400
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         "LEONARD D. BLADO" <BLADOLE@HSDWL.UTC.COM>
Subject:      Re: Rule questions

Pete Giannopoulos wrote:
> I have a coupole of rule question.
> 1)Can I choose to break subroutines in any order. For example
> I have Dhalia and only two bits can I break the end the run subroitine
> or does the trash a program subroutine hit me before I could break
> the end the run subroutine.

        Yes, you can choose to break subroutines in any order.  However,
no subroutines take effect until after you have "dealt" with all of
the subroutines- either broken them, failed to break them, or not
tried to break them, so it doesn't really matter.

> 2) If all the routines of a liche hit me ( 3 routines of do a brain
> damage) and I have Araska owns you in my hand can I use it
> or would they resolve seprately first makng me discard Araska and
> then flatlining me.

        They resolve separately- Arasaka Owns You is primarily an
anti-Bag card (although it is a tremendous resource to draw cards
in the right deck).

> 3)If something does more than one net damage who picks the order
> they hit the graveyard (important because of juckyard bbs)

        The Corp picks the cards one at a time, irrelevant of how
much damage is dealt.  That's the order they hit the trash (I'm
not sure what a "graveyard" is, though).

        -Len Blado
