Date:         Mon, 22 Jul 1996 15:44:00 +0100
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         Stephane Bura <bura@LAFORIA.IBP.FR>
Subject:      Re: NETRUNNER-L Digest - 15 Jul 1996 to 16 Jul 1996

Mike Foster answered to me:

>>Run when there is no risk
>...and you'll lose.

>>Run when you need it
>... and you're usually too late.

>>But the rest of the time, you must manage the risks. Could this card be a
>>Bolter Cluster? Is it worth a 4 net damage burn? Can I take a tag and
>>survive?
>And you'll get smoked every time by my speed corp deck with no damage and
>only one card that gives a tag. You'll be worried that a Rock is Strong is
>Bolter Cluster, and that I have a Trojan Horse and Urban Renewal, and by the
>time you're prepared to defend against these things that are merely figments
>of your imagination, you've given me a 4-6 point head start. And good luck
>stopping me from scoring the one more agenda I need to win, with Political
>Overthrow and Project Managers...

Maybe I was not very clear about the "risk" notion.
I didn't say that you shouldn't run if you might take some net damage.
I said that you should know if, in the following run, there is a chance that
you could be flatlined (or that the corp would gain a decisive advantage).
If the risk is zero, then you MUST run (or you should in about 90% of the cases.
However, your deck might require some preparation).

If the risk is different from zero, you must use the knowledge you have
about your opponent and his deck and run if you believe you have a fair
chance of hurting him more than he can hurt you.

I'm not paranoid. Most of the corps I play against find that I run far too
much for their taste.
But being a good runner is knowing when NOT to run, too.

--
Stephane Bura                                              bura@laforia.ibp.fr
