Date:         Mon, 22 Jul 1996 15:58:50 +0000
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         Philip Harvey G-Net 701 3371 <philip.harvey@GECM.COM>
Subject:      JOA/MFS

>> OK, Sparky, here you clearly states that with MFS you resolve the
>> trashing first, then gain bits. This should imply that if the
> >trashing is prevented, you gain no bits and the Joan/MFS combo
>> do not work. How can you then still say that the Joan/MFS combo
>> works?

>The point is that MFS still *trashes* the cards.  As far as it is
>concerned, it did what it had to do.  All it knows is that it sent
>those cards to the trash.
>The fact that they didn't actually get there is somewhat irrelevant,
>as far as MFS is concerned.

Um...  I thought it was the Runner that trashed the cards, not MFS.
This makes using JOA to save the programs you were willingly going to
trash even more ridiculous.

>If there were some card that you could use that if you paid bits would
>prevent cards from being trashed, you could not use the bits generated
>from MFS to pay for the prevention effects.

Why not?  You would have the bits available.

>So you resolve the trashing first -- MFS trashes the cards, and JOA or
>whatever rescues them -- and then you get the bits for the cards that
>MFS "trashed."

JOA does not *rescue* the cards.  It prevents them from hitting the
trash in the first place.  It's a prevention card.  It's preventative.
It prevents.


>HTH,
>Dave

------------------------------------------------

>Do trashing first not resolve trashing first. So You 1)trash 2)get bits
>3)then prevent trash.

No, no, no.  Read the FAQ for Edited Shipping Manifest.  It is implicit
that you cannot receive bits for an action and then prevent an effect
before that.
The correct order would be:
1.  Trash.
2.  Prevent trash.
3.  Get bits.  Or not.

>--
>Brian"SPOT"Dorricott                  \
>spotone@mindport.net                >{{}>
>http://www.mindport.net/~spotone      /

Pip
'Even a stopped clock gives the right time twice a day.'
