Date:         Mon, 22 Jul 1996 11:11:49 PDT
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         Bill Ingram <bing@ITS.BLDRDOC.GOV>
Subject:      Re: How to enjoy the game!!!

--- On Mon, 22 Jul 1996 18:46:00 EET  Lohann <lohann@AZTEC.CO.ZA> wrote:

>Here is what I do:
>
>Chuck ALOT of cards in a deck +/- 90 or so. (both sides) and play with what
>comes up. EVEN BETTER have 14 AGENDA points as V conditions and now you are
>talking FUN, STRATEGY etc.

>There we go, listen: DONT PLAY TO WIN, PLAY TO ENJOY!!!!

Terrific idea.  And, that's pretty much exactly the way I play most of my
NetRunner, MtG, Guardians, SCTCG, etc. games.  Unless I am trying a specific
theme (or feel I have to play a stronger deck just to have a chance in hell of
winning), I almost always play my decks as highlanders and specifically avoid
cards that are generally considered overpowered.  It's always fun and
interesting to play WITHOUT known and expected combos.  That way I have to
"fly by the seat of my pants" and use cards in unusual ways to win a game.

But, how do you get your opponents to play the same way?  All too often
I whip out my highlander deck and proceed to get thrashed by amazingly
degenerate decks.  "Well, I AM playing a fun deck," they say, "what's more
fun than winning in 6 turns?"

I've tried simply not playing against players known to play killer decks,
but suddenly that limits my potential opponents to almost no one.  And,
of course, in organized play (i.e., tournaments and leagues), you can't
refuse to play certain opponents.

How do the rest of you folks force your opponents to play non-killer decks?

-- Bill
