Date:         Mon, 22 Jul 1996 15:41:49 -0500
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         "Alex S. Kallend" <kallale@SNOOPY.CNS.IIT.EDU>
Subject:      Re: NETRUNNER-L Digest - 21 Jul 1996 to 22 Jul 1996
In-Reply-To:  <199607221916.MAA21108@oracle.wizards.com> from "Automatic digest
              processor" at Jul 22, 96 12:16:15 pm

> From:    Z <zonker@WESTWORLD.COM>
> Subject: Re: NETRUNNER-L Digest - 20 Jul 1996 to 21 Jul 1996
>
> >Perhaps you should pursue other interests...  :)
>
> I happen to agree with a lot of his points.  The object of any CCG is to
> create as much variety in deck construction as possible.  Unfortunately,
> after 13 weeks, Netrunner has proved that it's no better than most when
> originality comes into question.


I hate to break it to you, but this isn't a facet of CCG's, but rather a
reflection of human nature. People are inherently more willing to copy
something that works instead of thinking for themselves. This is why
copyrights, patents, etc. exist...

It was well posted on the magic list how one of the players in the first
Pro Tour game copied his winning deck from someone else just the night
before.... Anything to win, eh?

It appears bad in CCG's because
1) someone will play something new, and then post about it
2) everyone who reads the net will try it, and also post about it.
They'll spread it locally also.

3) people are gullible. If you say something works, people will believe
it works, and if it loses for them, they'll blame it on luck
I've seen so many copies of bad magic decks that someone posted "hey this
deck kicks butt" and they all just accept it happily. The JoA/MfS stuff
is another one. Someone got it to work a couple times, posted, and
althoguh there are a lot of posts saying how long it takes to get the
setup going, because it was posted, people will play it.


The way to have a creative game is to have things spread slowly. Don't
post decks that work, make people think for themselves, and there will be
a much more creative game.


Alex
