Date:         Mon, 22 Jul 1996 17:51:25 -0700
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         "David R. Liu" <davidliu@VIOLET.BERKELEY.EDU>
Subject:      Enough Already!!!

The title says it all... enough!  If we spent as much effort discussing
Netrunner strategy instead of whining/debating about JOA/MFS, we would
probably find Netrunner to be even more interesting.

Let it be know (as almost everyone already knows):
- That Wizards has ruled that JOA/MFS is legal, for now.  It is, in their
own words, legal because JOA/MFS is consistent with the intended function
of Joan of Arc.  This doesn't mean they foresaw the combo; it simply
means they feel this combo does not violate any of THEIR principles
behind JOA or MFS as they originally conceived these principles.

- Wizards DESIGNED this game (as the last Duelist says in a footnote,
"Tom Wylie *is* the rules") and therefore it is safe to conclude that
they have spent a great deal of careful thought in constructing rules and
in making rules judgements.  Does anyone honestly believe that Wizards
ruled this way simply to piss off their customers?  Does anyone
think the rules staff at Wizards is simply stupider than he or she?
I believe the design of a good CCG is incredibly difficult, and I
strongly feel that there are levels of design considerations far deeper
than any of us currently understand.

I'm not saying I would have ruled the same way that Wizards did, nor
am I saying that everyone *must* play by the Wizards ruling.  But to
say that "you can't use JOA/MFS" is simply wrong.  Everyone is free
to play the game as you feel, but in tourneys until Wizards changes their
ruling (at least official tourneys), JOA/MFS is LEGAL.

Realistically, this does not in my opinion change the Netrunner landscape
in a major way.  Sure the JOA/MFS combo is a great way to get money.  It
suffers from other problems however, and I have actually witnessed or played
more JOA/MFS decks LOSE than WIN (about 10 games total).

I still think that the most important factor in the success of either side is
the way you play your cards and not the cards themselves.

So... anyone have any good Roving Sub stories?  :)

Regards,
David
