From:         Mike Foster <mfoster1@VOYAGER.NET>
Subject:      Re: Submarine Uplink vs. Jack Attack

At 11:13 AM 7/19/96 -0500, you wrote:

>Maybe the card was meant to prevent all attempts and maybe the card
>should be reworded to say "For the remainder of this run the runner
>cannot jack out this effect cannot be prevented"

But it can be prevented. There just aren't any cards that currently do so.

>but it DOESNT so it
>should be played the way it is read wich means the runner cannot elect
>to jack out.

Where in the HELL do you get that?!? <warning, flame alert>
Play it the way it's read? No, you're playing it the way you think it ought
to be! Maybe you need a few more (hundred) English lessons, but "elect" is
not an implied verb in the sentence "Runner cannot jack out".
"Runner cannot jack out" means <gasp> that the runner *can't* jack out. It
doesn't matter if the jacking out in question is voluntary or not! J-A
prevents it! Quit putting words on the card that don't exist, and maybe
you'll understand the rules a little better.

>The Submarine Uplink is not elective.

Sure it is. You're never forced to use Sub Uplink.
Never mind... I'm breaking my promise to myself to never talk to you about
this again... I'll shut up now.
