Date:         Tue, 23 Jul 1996 08:54:05 -0400
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         "LEONARD D. BLADO" <BLADOLE@HSDWL.UTC.COM>
Subject:      Re: Tycho Extension vs. Political Overthrow

> Main thing about Tycho Extension is that it can be scored in 1 turn
> through fast process. Even with 2 project consultants, you can't score
> political overthrow in 1 turn. Also, after you score Political overthrow,
> you still have to score another agenda.. lets say its a 3/1 agenda. The
> cost of scoring 1 tycho and 1 4/3 (or 3/3) is much less than scoring the
> 9/6 and 3/1.

        When people put Political Overthrow in a deck, they put it in
almost exclusively to trim the Agenda percentage of their deck.  Most
decks with Political Overthrow never plan to score the darn thing anyway,
or to score it when they have such dominance over the game that the
'Runner can't do anything about an Agenda advanced over the course
of 3 turns.  Take a look at these two decks:
        Tycho Deck: 5 Tycho in a 50 card deck (10% of deck is Agendas)
        PO Deck: 3 Political Overthrow in a 45 card deck (6-7% of deck is
                Agendas)

        If the first action the 'Runner takes is to simply play
Custodial Position and run, then against the Tycho deck, he has around
a 28% chance to score an Agenda- against the Political Overthrow deck,
he has around a 19% chance to score an Agenda.  Considering that with
either of these decks, you have to score 2 Agenda to win (barring
some special use 'Runner cards), these odds start to build up rather
significantly.
        While most decks aren't "one Agenda" decks like the above,
the trimming effect remains much the same- it severely reduces the
odds that you will get nailed for a "cheapie" early in the game.

        It's not that Tycho Extension is bad, or Political Overthrow
good- just that they have very different uses.

        -Len Blado
