Date:         Tue, 23 Jul 1996 11:03:36 -0600
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         Greg Dglas Teed <ac419@SFN.SASKATOON.SK.CA>
Subject:      Re: Assorted Rulings
In-Reply-To:  <31F3FDFB@smtpgate.osan.af.mil>

On Tue, 23 Jul 1996, Stoneburne J SrA 51CS/SCUBS wrote:

> >I have a coupole of rule question.
> >1)Can I choose to break subroutines in any order. For example
> >I have Dhalia and only two bits can I break the end the run subroitine
> >or does the trash a program subroutine hit me before I could break
> >the end the run subroutine.
>
>   You must take each subroutine in order. I believe that rule is in the
> book.

   Ice subroutines are dealt with (either broken or not) in the order the
runner chooses. Then after it is determined what subroutines are broken
or not, the unbroken subroutines affect the runner in the order they are
listed on the ice card.
   For example: Black Dahlia encounters a Banpei. The runner has three
bits. The runner may choose to break the "End the run" subroutine,
leaving the "Trash a program" subroutine unbroken. Now that all the
subroutines are dealt with, the unbroken subroutines affect the runner,
in order. A program is trashed and, since the "end the run" subroutine is
broken, the ice is passed.

    As a side note: One of the best features of M:TG is the rule that
Upkeep costs *must* be addressed. We would do well to adopt this "must
address" ruling for ice subroutines, so that there is no argument about
forgetting to break a subroutine (or missing the text on the ice card).
Mastiff is particularly easy to make a mistake on.

- dglas (I could put something in gibberish here if I wanted to.)

