Bit value: 0 (random musing)

The great chess teacher C.J.S. Purdy recommended in the course of planning
at chess that the player ask himself, "if I had two moves in a row, what
would I do?" The idea was that the player released himself from the
inhibiting thought process, "I go there, he goes there, I go there," and
who knows? -- maybe the opponent will waste a move.

I have tried to adapt that kind of thinking to NetRunner deck construction
by asking, "what is the absolute best situation for this card to be played
in?", forgetting for a moment that NetRunner and chess are not played in
vacuums and that the hideous opponents are always there trying to muck us
up.

For instance, Synchronized Attack on HQ is best when the corporation is
bitless. Therefore, ideally, we would like to play a Priority Wreck to run
on HQ, then make him spend a bunch of bits, and *then* Synchro Attack him.
So, gain a bunch yourself before Priority Wrecking, but not by using Joan
and misc. :) Playful AI for a couple dozen, then Priority Wreck, then
Synchro Attack.

Hey, like I said, we're just dreaming here. :)

I was contemplating virii earlier, and it seems to me that a Bodyweight
Data Creche, Karl deVeres, and a Wilson Doofusweefle work great with
Incubator. (I repeat that in this dream state we don't care about Chance
Observations.) Take four actions, then run the archives with Wilson. Hit
'im with an incubate counter, and earn a bit. Creche run, another incubate,
another bit. Eventually, when you eventually infect the corporation with a
destructive virust (Cascade/Skiviss/what have you), you'll be rolling for
who-knows-how-many incubators.

Frisco_Del_Rosario@cattekin.vip.best.com
"Beaver damming the informathion thuperhighway thinthe 1994."
