Well, it is clear that Nanosurgeons takes place *after* the damage is
prevented.  You were not damaged.

With MFS one could argue that the effects happen simultaneously -- the
cards are trashed and you get the bits.  Immediately afterwards, you
prevent the trashing (during the prevention phase), and the programs
remain untrashed.

If MFS said gain 3 bits for each prgram that was trashed last action or last turn,
then it would be more parallel to Lifesaver Nanosurgeons.

> If the rules team can't resolve, or at least discuss important issues such
> as these, there probably shouldn't be a rules team.  DO NOT take this to
> mean that I think Proteus should go on the back burner.  Proteus should
> certainly be #1.

I think that the rules team has ruled on this, and that your flame and
suggestion that they are not doing their job is unwarrented,
ill-considered, and uninformed.

