Date:         Tue, 23 Jul 1996 15:36:21 -0700
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         Glenn Elliott <gee@WIZARDS.COM>
Subject:      Re: Submarine Uplink vs. Jack Attack

>> Play it the way it's read? No, you're playing it the way you think it ought
>> to be! Maybe you need a few more (hundred) English lessons, but "elect" is
>> not an implied verb in the sentence "Runner cannot jack out".
>
>Umn the elect part was part of someone elses quote that I snipped it
>came from Glen(n?) (one of the game designers I believe.)

Two n's, and yes I'm a game designer.  I didn't actually work on
Netrunner (I was working on Armed & Dangerous at the time), but
I did work on Proteus and am now .... !@((@$$( [transmission
interrupted]

But sorry, can't pin that one on me.  I never used the word "elect"
in my posts on this subject.

"Try" and "choose", yes, but not "elect".  :-)

Jack Attack doesn't prevent the Runner from *trying* to jack out,
it prevents the Runner from *succeeding*.

Submarine Uplink forces the Runner to try to jack out.  No, the
card doesn't have the words "try to" on it, they are implied.  Jack
Attack makes the result (in this case, successfully jacking out)
impossible, so the Runner's attempt fails.

Note that if Submarine Uplink was worded differently, Jack
Attack would not prevent it from working.  If it said "Submarine
Uplink jacks you out" then it would not be the Runner making
the attempt and so Jack Attack would not prevent the attempt
from succeeding.

Glenn
