Date:         Tue, 23 Jul 1996 20:21:26 -0400
Reply-To:     gandalf@fast.net
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         Zack Weintraub <gandalf@FAST.NET>
Subject:      Re: NETRUNNER-L Digest - 21 Jul 1996 to 22 Jul 1996

> You know what I really have a problem with?  If the trashing can be
> prevented, but you still gain bits, why can't you prevent damage with a
> Force Shield and then use Lifesaver Nanosurgeons?  The whole argument for
> this lies in the following question, which was never answered when I
> presented it as a rebuttal last week:  Does a Force Shield AUTOMATICALLY
> prevent damage, or can you choose to let that damage pass through?  If you
> can choose to let it through, then you also have to choose to prevent it.
> Therefore, by the JOA/MFS illogic, this combo should work, too.  What, I
> didn't take damage?  Well, you didn't trash any programs!
>
> Either both have to be illegal, or both have to be legal.  You all know
> where I stand.
>
> -Zonker

Sorry, not true.  Nanosurgeons say "if you take damage", and because of
Force Shield you don't take damage.  Joan of Arc prevents trashing, but
Misc. doesn't give bits for what cards are trashed, but what cards were
attempted to be trashed.  Programs going to trash isin't a cost of M-F-S,
but taking damage has to happen (can't be prevented) if you want to draw
cards.

---Zack (who said he would get into this argument) Weintraub

