Date:         Wed, 24 Jul 1996 08:34:58 -0400
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         "LEONARD D. BLADO" <BLADOLE@HSDWL.UTC.COM>
Subject:      Several Replies

Glenn wrote:
> We *might* change one or both of the cards which *might* make
> the current ruling irrelevant.  *If* we change the cards, we may or
> may not issue errata for the v1.0 versions of the cards.  If we do not
> issue errata for them, however, they will continue to be played
> according to the current ruling.

        Well, I'd like to voice a request that you institute a general
policy of "most current wording" on cards- that is, whether or not
specifically stated, the latest version of a card has the official
wording and errata applied to it, and all older versions must follow
it.  It ends up being a LOT simpler in the long run, and avoids much
confusion as people try and figure out what errata applies to what
versions of a card (more to the point, it ensures all cards function
in a consistent manner).

> None of *us* are particularly thrilled that there is a degenerate
> combo in Netrunner, either, but we're not going to go off willy-nilly
> and change rules, rulings, and/or cards just to fix one combo.  WotC
> has tried that before, and I think you're familiar with the results.

        Gosh darn it! It's *not* degenerate.  Misc.For-Sale can serve
as a good source of late-game bits.  It functions that way WITH or
WITHOUT Joan of Arc.  In a good deck, you're unlikely to have the
50-60 Imps that make it a truly disgusting engine... if you do, you'll
lose the game far before you ever draw the Misc.For-Sale or the Joan
of Arc.  Let's face it- in the late game, you're ALWAYS going to have
a pile of stuff you can safely trash, provided you think you're going
to win soon.  Whether or not you prevent these things from going to
the trash generally ends up being irrelevant, as they weren't terribly
useful to begin with.

James Stoneburner wrote:
> Huh! Well, that makes me look at the card in a completely different light.
> However, I have a question. Doesn't this basically make Speed Trap a
> useless card against ambush nodes, since most of them have that
> phrase on there?

        Of the 11 Ambushes in the game, 1 (VTS) is useable while not
rezzed, and 2 more are useable from HQ/R&D.  The rest must be both
installed and rezzed to use (which might be why you don't see them
that much).  Note that all of the really nasty ones are like this
(Vacant Soulkiller, Experimental AI).

Stephane wrote:
> Brian Bankler wrote:
>>        If you have 2+ Corp negotiating centers, do you get the bits for
>>revealing agendas from each one?
>
> I thought about this myself.
> I don't think so. CNC gives you the opportunity to gain bits. Two or
> more CNCs don't give you more opportunities, IMO.
> But I could be wrong.

        Much as I hate to disagree with the downtrodden souls who have
yet to acquire a Wall of Ice (hell... if you're that desperate I'll
send you one- I've got like 7 of the useless things), look at CNC:

Corporate Negotiating Center     0 3 Node-Asset
     At the start of each of your turns, gain 1* for each [agenda] card stored
     in HQ that you show to Runner.
     "That which does not get me fired makes me more valuable to the
     corporation- Dave Michaels, Microtech Special Ops"
     (Roger Coad)

        Since you have have multiple "start of turn" effects, you can
simply keep showing the 'Runner Agendas in your hand to gain bits with
multiple CNC's out (just as if you multiple Braindance Campaign out,
you would get to use them all).  BTW: Another reason to love CNC is
the fact that it has a rez cost of 0 and a trash cost of 3...

        -Len Blado
