From:         David Orr <dmorr@SOFTWARE.NET>
Subject:      Re: For Sparky!
In-Reply-To:  <199607240922.FAA23142@vixa.voyager.net> from "Mike Foster" at
              Jul 24, 96 05:22:25 am

> >>Therefore, using Lifesaver Nanosurgeons after preventing
> >> damage should work, if one is using the very same illogic that spawned
> JOA/MFS.
> >
> >Well, it is clear that Nanosurgeons takes place *after* the damage is
> >prevented.  You were not damaged.
> >
> >With MFS one could argue that the effects happen simultaneously -- the
> >cards are trashed and you get the bits.  Immediately afterwards, you
> >prevent the trashing (during the prevention phase), and the programs
> >remain untrashed.
>
> Excuse me, but how do you propose to "prevent" something that's already
> happened?
> Well, I'll be going now, before I get re-embroiled in this arguement, loose
> my cool again, and have multiple people tell me how immature I'm being...
>
> >If MFS said gain 3 bits for each prgram that was trashed last action or
> last turn,
> >then it would be more parallel to Lifesaver Nanosurgeons.
>
> Gain 3 bits for each program trashed. If you prevented the trashing, no
> programs were trashed. If the programs are already trashed, then it's too
> late to prevent the trashing.


How about this. You decide to go wash your car.  After you wash your
car, in celebration of its being clean, you will buy yourself an ice
cream -- heck, you'll give yourself an ice cream for each car you
wash.  So you go and wash your car, and because you're hungry, your
neighbor's car as well.  Unfortunately, you're also lazy.  So you take
the cars to the car wash place, and send them in.

In celebration for having washed the cars, you go to 31 Flavors and
buy yourself two cones of ice cream.

Meanwhile, your mean landlady Joan, who hates cleanliness of any sort,
sneaks in to the car wash and disables the machine, preventing the cars
from being washed.  You come out, happily finishing off the last of the
Mocha Almond Fudge you got in a huge waffle cone, only to find that,
tragically, that the cars are not, in fact, washed.

Yet this strange thing has happened.  You told yourself, honestly,
that you would give yourself a cone for each car you washed.  And you
did in fact wash the car -- how were you supposed to know that Joan
would maliciously and cruelly prevent your car from being washed, for
no good reason that you can see.  And, of course, it's much too late
to give the ice cream back.  What do you do?

Wow, I almost feel sorry for that poor Misc.For-Sale.

Thanks,
Dave

