Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         "Marc \"Sparky\" Schmalz" <flatline@WIZARDS.COM>
Organization: Wizards of the Coast
Subject:      Re: Card rulings and Proteus

Byron Massey wrote:
> My first question is to Sparky. I read your post where you ask for patien=
ce in
> regards to Joan of Arc/Misc. for Sale and also the recent question about =
the
> Arasaka Portable Prototype/Shell Traders.

The misc.for-sale errata was just posted.  The Shell Traders decisions were=
 =

made long ago, and I don't see them changing.  Here's my file of errata,
interpretations, and rulings for Shell Traders:

Original Wording:
A: Choose a program or hardware card from your hand. Set that card aside, a=
nd =

put a number of Shell counters on it equal to its installation cost. When t=
he =

last Shell counter on that card has been removed, install that card, at no =

cost. Remove one Shell counter from one card at the start of each of your t=
urns.
[1]: Remove one Shell counter from a card.

Errata:
A: Choose a program or hardware card from your hand. Set that card aside, a=
nd =

put a number of Shell counters on it equal to its installation cost. When t=
he =

last Shell counter on that card has been removed, install that card, at no =

cost. =

[1]: Remove one Shell counter from a card.
Remove one Shell counter from one card at the start of each of your turns.

Interpretations/Rulings:
* Card is set aside face-up so Corp can verify the number of Shell counters=
 =

placed on it.

* Each copy can remove 1 counter from any card that has them.

* If Shell Traders is removed from play, any cards with Shell counters on =

them remain =8Cin limbo=B9 and can have their counters removed by subsequen=
t =

copies of Shell Traders.

* "At no cost" means the regular bit cost of a card.  If a card states that=
 =

it has additional installation costs, you must pay them.  If another card =

indicates that additional costs must be paid to install the card being =

processed by Shell Traders, you must pay that cost.

* If you remove the last counter from a program and don't have any free MU,=
 =

you MUST overwrite an existing program.

* If you remove the last counter from a card that has additional costs to =

install and you have those resources, you MUST spend them and install the c=
ard.

* If you CANNOT pay the additional costs, you lose the opportunity to insta=
ll =

that card, and it slips into limbo permanently; remove it from the game.

> My final question is about the ICE card Ball and Chain. This seemed like =
a
> really cool card, one I used a lot, when I played with it using the *comm=
on
> sense* interpretation of how it worked. But when Rob Leachman told me how=
 WOTC
> wanted it to work, it vanished from my deck (and everyone else I have eve=
r
> played) and has never returned. What problems are being avoided by playin=
g Ball
> and Chain in this strange way (letting the runner see the next ICE before=

> deciding whether or not to pay for the Ball and Chain)? I hope it avoids =
some
> terrible problem, because this ruling has turned this card into notepaper=
=2E

Very simply - that's the way the card is worded. =


"*For the remainder of the run, Runner must pay [2] when encountering a pie=
ce =

of ice, in addition to any other costs, or end the run."

Now if the card read "...Runner must pay [2] when _approaching_ a piece of =

ice..." that would be a different story.  However, encountering ice happens=
 =

after the Corp has had a chance to rez it.  It's a good card for stopping =

the Runner, but isn't good in a Black Ice deck.  Not all cards can be =

everything to everyone.

> I guess I'm just saying I could go along with these rulings if someone at=
 WOTC
> would just post something explaining what problems are being avoided by k=
eeping
> these apparently contradictory rules.

There are no 'problems' being avoided here - we're explaining how the cards=
 =

work. Some people will find the interpretations counter-intuitive and some =

will agree with our official interpretations of the card wordings (and it =

usually depends on whether or not you just lost against an opponent using =

the card :^).  We learned a long time ago that we can't please everyone!

> As for Proteus, I agree with the person that was concerned about the rele=
ase
> coming too early. I have had difficulty getting people interested in Netr=
unner
> in my area, and adding an expansion with new victory conditions is only g=
oing
> to make the situation worse. =


The new 'victory conditions' are as evident as poison counters in Magic.  =

Each card explains the new rule right on it - at least the ones that have =

something to do with bad publicity.

