> I can't tell anything about the lurkers (whom I DON'T suspect of being
> preying leeches spying our every posts), but the people who post here
> seem pretty imaginative to me, even sometimes in their interpretation
> of the rules ;)

There are lots of lurkers, both on mailing lists, and newsgroups. Maybe
it's not as rampant in netrunner as it is in magic, but I'm guessing it's
the same for all CCG's, from experience & talking to people. As large
tournaments become widespread, more of it will happen.

Maybe it's a depressing way to look at human nature, but it's the only
thing that really explains why in magic (IMHO), tournaments are dominated by
clones of decks that have proven to win tournaments.


> If I hadn't some fun reading this list, I would simply stop.
> And *of course* people are happy to copy other's (good) ideas. Isn't it
> the whole point of discussion? (a good example being that only two posts
> were enough to convince me to try to use CNC - see below)
>

sure, but there is a difference between discussion and outright plagarism
discussion is what happened when you asked about CNC. Plagarism is when
You post a deck, and I take it to tournaments, and play it as if it were
my own. Discussion is good. Plagarism is what really makes CCG's look bad
and uncreative.

I'm not saying that anyone in particular is guilty of anything. I don't
have any way of knowing who made the first 23 imp deck... I don't care,
but when I see posts complaining about the lack of creativity, in
netrunner, and CCG's in general, I start to wonder, do our discussion
groups do more harm than good...

> >i dunno about the CNC, however, what is so obvious about why you wouldn't
