Subject:      Re: Degenerate
In-Reply-To:  <31F6BD26.57A@mindport.net> from "Brian \"SPOT\" Dorricott" at
              Jul 24, 96 07:17:42 pm

> 12 to 20 bits by turn 2 hmm lets see turn one actions 4
> install 4 imps
> turn 2 actions four
> install JOA  draw  card play MFS pay one bit to return MFS net gain 14
> bits zero cards in hand no runs done and no agendas scored.
>
> Ok meanwhile on a similar note
> Turn one 4 actions
> SCORE SCORE SCORE SCORE
> net gain 16 bits for four cards one card left in hand turn two available
> for running
>
> Ok sounds good to me I think I will just run out and buy me some more
> JOA and MFS... NOT!

Umm.. well, this is really a moot point now that the new ruling is out
(yea!) but I feel the need to defend my initial point.

If you have a deck that can consistantly (ie. over 90%) get 4 scores
out in the first 2 turns and still be a well constructed deck, I want
to see it.  The thing about the (now defunct) JOA/MFS deck that I was
playing is that you can get that out every single game.  Every game
you can depend on getting 12+ bits the second turn, or failing that,
15+ bits the 3rd round.  AND, you are installing useful things all
the while.

BTW, it's nothing as inefficient as you describe.  By turn 3, I've
also gone through about half of the deck and played everything it
needs to play which is another virtue over score x4; at the moment by
turn 7 the (now defunct) deck has everything it needs to start running
and is accessing about 10 cards per turn by turn 10 (well, that assumes
it doesn't encounter any agenda -- I figure you're smart enough to
know what that means).  With a little tuning, I think that the deck
could have reduced turn 7 to turn 5 and turn 10 to turn 7.

And yes, it did have tag protection (quite a bit as a matter of fact).

>
> Dont you guys understand the JOA/MFS combo SUCKS if you happen to draw a
> MFS on turn 12 or so after you already have your well built deck going
> and are just looking for some extra bits or so for that one last run or
> if you happen to have a JOA out then you can probably score some major
> bits in the late game, But by then a good deck doesn't really need alot
> of bits. By turn 12 my clown deck is running bitless for at least 3 runs
> a turn using a good deck and a couple of stealth cards installed in
> Affreets 3 clowns in another and a suite of breakers around (don't have
> a bartmoss yet)
> By turn 12 my other deck is running also pretty much bitless due to
> keeping the CORP so poor very little ICE has been rezzed to cause me to
> have to pay bits.
> IN the early game there are better cards to score money that don't
> require you to draw a combo of five cards. Get real just because someone
> once posted that he scored big with JOA/MFS (and don't doubt you can
> because it truly can be awesome in late game but once again who cares
> except for psychological advantage) doesnt mean it is a KILLER COMBO
> what it is, is a moderately good idea that has as much degenerative
> ability as trojan horse/Urban Renewal and I dont see anyone clamoring to
> ban this combo.

Blah.  Maybe I just haven't seen it, but I've haven't seen an trojan
horse deck.  Between 2 fall guys, a wilson, a junkyard, a ESC, and
some ability to gain bits, you'd have to be a very wily corp to be able
to bag the runner.

My friend plays instead with 2 full body conversions and an armored
fridge as well as other tag protection.  That works pretty well as well.

-- Ed


