Date:         Wed, 24 Jul 1996 18:21:04 -0700
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         Foolkiller <cwagner@CWO.COM>
Subject:      Social Engineering

Hey folks.

Here's something for everybody.  When you play Social Engineering,
what do you do with the bits you don't put into your hand?

Do you leave them on the table?  Pick them up with your other hand?

What I'm getting at is, is it OK for the Corp player to count the
bits you did not pick up?  In casual play I guess this doesn't
happen much, but I'm concerned with tournament etiquette in this
case.

I think that the Runner should pick up all bits, take the amount
they want into one hand while keeping the others in a closed fist
above the table.  They extend the hand with the selected bits
while the Corp player guesses. Then the Runner opens their hand
to reveal the outcome.  I'm just thinking that its too easy to
keep tabs on the Runner's bit pool, and thus to nullify the card.

Anyone?  Everyone?

-----------------

On a related note, if the Runner chooses an unrezzed piece of
ICE to pass after successfully using Social Engineering, can the
Corp still rez the ICE as the Runner passes?  I think so, 'cause
the Runner still approaches the ICE before passing it, and that is
when we rez the ICE.


SeeYa,
Foolkiller
cwagner@cwo.com
