Date:         Tue, 23 Jul 1996 08:58:24 -0800
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         Byron Massey <Byron.Massey@THEGATE.HOTLIN.FIDONET.ORG>
Organization: Fidonet: The Computer Hotline! BBS
Subject:      What this list is for?

Stephane Bura wrote:

 L> This list is just a cool way to get fast answers to strange questions,
 L> to meet weird people, to discuss about the game and to obtain
 L> information from WotC.
 L> It's not a mean to pressure R&D into changing the rules.

I've recently reached the conclusion that no matter which way you lean on
JOA/MFS, it really doesn't unbalance the game. *But*

I suffered through a couple years of bizarre rulings on the *other* WotC game,
and I have to tell you, the main reason I switched to Netrunner was its
beautiful, balanced design and its (initially) lack of a need for "rulings" of
any type.

So along comes a two-card combo that can generate a ton of bits, even though it
defies the first-glance, common sense interpretation of how cards in this game
work. People on both sides of the argument write eloquent defenses of their
positions. Some write ugly ones :) Suddenly, some of the fun of *no longer
playing Magic* has been leached by this ruling. Do I still play Netrunner and
love it? Of course I do. But for all of us who arrived at this game from Magic,
this apparent move onto the slippery slope that ends with huge "timing
flowcharts" and scads of rulings for particular cards is really hard to take.

I disagreee with Stephane. I think this list *must* be a place where people
question the consistency and validity of rulings. Where else could this happen?
Isn't that one of the great things about being American?

I don't think this list is a good place to meet "weird people".

 L> Btw, why would you want to antagonize Sparky? He's a Netrep so,
 L> except on some occasions when he's ill or very tired ;) , he's right.

Being in charge of something *doesn't mean you're "always right"*! I doubt
Sparky would make that claim. Part of being a good leader or arbitrator is
being able to admit and correct earlier mistakes. They've certainly reversed
many rulings (some more than once) in *the other game*.

-Byron

I could agree with Stephane if I wanted to.



