Date:         Thu, 25 Jul 1996 12:37:16 PDT
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         Bill Ingram <bing@ITS.BLDRDOC.GOV>
Subject:      Re: Stupider Cheaters

--- On Thu, 25 Jul 1996 08:13:26 -0600  Greg Dglas Teed <ac419@SFN.SASKATOON.SK.CA> wrote:

>   This, and other reasons, is why, when I'm making a decision like this,
>I simply determine the number of bits I "set aside" randomly. Corp
>players soon learn to stop trying to psych out a die roll.

Actually, if I were the Corp and I knew that you were rolling a die to
determine how many bits to set aside, I'd simply choose the highest number
you could roll.  Your strategy would indeed reduce the chance that I could
outthink you, but when I was right, I'd always hit you for the maximum
bits.

Then, of course, you'd have to think about changing your mind whenever
you rolled a high number.  And, once you start thinking about your move,
I could start to outthink you again.

>   I also use dice to determine what cards I'll pull from the Corp's hand
>during a successful run on HQ (assuming I don't have *very good* reason
>to do otherwise).

There's a lot of information you can learn from picking a specific card.
For example, when I earn the right to draw a card, I quickly reach out
and put my fingers near a card and then pause.  Often, if I am at an
Agenda card, the opponent will flinch and say, "Hold it, let me mix them."
That tells me that there is at least one "good" card in his hand.  If
he doesn't flinch, I know I'm at a non-trashable card and select a different
one.

--- On Thu, 25 Jul 1996 19:11:48 +0200  MOAH <moah@MICRONET.FR> wrote:

>I know of a cheating attempt in Chess. The guy asked to go to the toilets
>and went to a stand where magazine were sold (Chess mags, of course) and
>started reading magazines about the situation on the board he was playing
>(Am i clear ? I don't feel so). But the other player had gone for a walk
>too, and saw him. So he grasped the guy, with the mag open, and brought
>him to the referees, the book still open at the good page.

If I were the referee, I wouldn't consider that cheating.  That's simply
doing some research.  Likewise, I wouldn't call it cheating if he brought
some index cards that had different suggestions as to what to do in
difficult situations.  Of course, I suppose the Chess tournament has
rules against this kind of thing, so technically it is against the rules,
but I wouldn't personally consider it cheating.  Moving the pieces when you
shouldn't or playing Metalica on your boombox while your opponent is thinking
are what I consider cheating.

Likewise, if someone came to an MtG or NetRunner tournament with a crib
sheet that explained what to do with certain cards and in certain situations,
I would not consider it cheating.  I would actually consider it a smart move.

-- Bill
