Date:         Thu, 25 Jul 1996 18:02:23 -0400
Reply-To:     gandalf@fast.net
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         Zack Weintraub <gandalf@FAST.NET>
Subject:      Re: "Decking" the corp

Edward Chen wrote:
> > [I believe Brian "SPOT" Dorricott wrote:]
> > deck) I have never heard of a corp losing by running out of cards. This
> > indicates to me that most games are between 7 to 25 turns in length the
> > possibility of scoring usable bits with JOA/MFS usually exists around
> > turn 14 or so this is which places it right in the middle of this
> > average (ok a little to the low side) this seems like a mildly pleasent
> > (for the runner) situation but hardly degenerate.
>
> Hmm.. I think it probably depends on the decks, but 7 to 25 seems about
> right.  I think I've seen some games go to 30 and rarely a game to
> 35, but that's because my corp decks suck.  :)

I have seen very short games, where the Corp ran out of cards.  The corp
didn't protect R+D very well for a few turns cause they used planning
consultants and they had no agenda in atleast 5 turns.  Runner played a Skivviss
and made a few runs.  Corp was happy cause it filled up his hand, while
not paying attention to the size of his r+d.  he worked up to about 7
counters before he realized that it was killing him.  he had about 10
cards left in library when he (past tense of forgo, forgoed, forgot?)
his next three actions.  Runner gave him another 3 counters (help from
Weefie) and the corp new he would have to forgo more actions, but if he
did, he would take more counters, so he conceded (a turn or so before
he would have lost).  Closest I've ever seen.  It was about 8-10 turns
long.

---Zack

