From:         "Marc \"Sparky\" Schmalz" <flatline@WIZARDS.COM>
Organization: Wizards of the Coast
Subject:      Re: Miscellaneous mailings which I don't think are right!

Richard Heath wrote:
>
> Reading the digest this morning I found a couple of mails which jump out at
> me as being completly incorrect.
>
> 1) Here's a neat one I encountered recently. A runner (using a Blink/Dropp
> >deck) used Crash Everett to draw two from his stack. He then kept one and
> >put the second card (a program) into his Microtech Backup Drive instead
> >of the trash. Whaddaya know...Crash sez "trash."
>
> Erm, I don't think so :-
>
> "Whenever one or more INSTALLED programs are being sent to the trash
> at the same time, you may instead choose to put any or all of the
> programs on top of Microtech Backup Drive in any order you choose.
> If Backup Drive is removed from play, trash any cards on it.
> (A): Bring the top card on Backup Drive into your hand."
>
> A card in your hand is not installed!

Right.

> 2) There seems to be a lot of discussion about whether Dropp will "end the
> run" after a jack attack has stopped the runner "jacking out".
> That's just it look at what I have just written. They are two different
> things. Ending the run can occur at any time. Jacking out is the choice
> the runner has before approaching the next piece of ice. Dropp ends the run
> which is defined in the FAQ :-
>
> Q: When does Dropp(TM) end the run?
>
> A: Dropp(TM) ends the run after the Runner finishes the piece of ice he or
> she was encountering when it was used. Future editions of Dropp(TM) will
> have the following word change to clarify: "<Picture: 0>: Break all
> subroutines on a piece of ice and end your run." "
>
> This is before the runner gets chance to jack out, so is a different thing!

Right.  Ending the run and jacking out are not the same, so your run can be
ended even if a card prevents you from jacking out.

