Date:         Thu, 25 Jul 1996 16:11:48 -0800
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         Frisco Del Rosario <Frisco_Del_Rosario@CATTEKIN.VIP.BEST.COM>
Subject:      Dirty rotten cheating dogs

Someone said: "I'd guess it's even rarer for somebody to cheat in
tournament chess."

Cheating at chess gets worse all the time. The reigning world champion was
caught on video taking a move back a few years ago. Some people will hold
their clock buttons down for the duration of a time scramble. Some throw
their pieces on intersections during blitz games and force their opponents
to adjust them, or even worse, pretend the piece was on either of the two
possible squares, depending on the course of events. There are innumerable
instances of games being fixed after accounting for the prize-winning
expectancies of the parties involved.

Cheating at NetRunner is a newer beast, of course, since chess as we know
it is 500 years old, and NetRunner is, um, not quite that.

Along with the already-mentioned "draw a Setup! from HQ and ignore it, or
from RD and Microtech AI Interface it away," one also has to be wary of one
who brings two Crash Everett cards too close to hand, keeping both, then
trashing something useless. And I'd be *really* leery of someone who played
with Bartmoss, Playful AI, and Vacuum Link and rolled a whole lot of twos,
but who winced at the suggestion of playing with Blink or Quest for
Cattekin. ;)

Frisco_Del_Rosario@cattekin.vip.best.com
"Beaver damming the informathion thuperhighway thinthe 1994."
