From:         Z <zonker@WESTWORLD.COM>
Subject:      Re: NETRUNNER-L Digest - 24 Jul 1996 to 25 Jul 1996

>Hey Zonker take a toke ok :) <----that is to take the sting of what I
>said. You should be happy havent you read the ruling errata today you
>have won. While I personally have always thought JOA/MFS was perfectly
>fine, I really think the new wording is HIGHLY ACCEPTABLE and does a
>great job of removing any ambiguity so what that the decision on how the
>cards worked was reversed I never found the combo that usefull anyway.
>And Hey I am happy too my SUL is now doing what I always said it would.

I'm pleased with the errata, but I do not take the position that I won.
This was a war, and nobody wins in war.  If you want an analogy, I feel like
a survivor who is relieved that the fighting and destruction are over.

I can't rub it in, mainly because there were two airtight explanations, one
for each side.

And for all of you rules teamers out there, the fact that there were two
completely feasible explanations for the same problem meant that errata of
some kind in the rules (or the cards) actually WAS necessary.  The JOA/MFS
combo could not be officially resolved any other way.

Take, for example, the card Preying Mantis.  Without the words "this damage
cannot be prevented", it would generate a similar effect.  Such wordings
seem to suggest that Richard Garfield may not have intended the prevention
of a cost to still generate the desired effect, and that MFS may have been
an aberration.

AND LASTLY (I only capitalize to draw attention to this particular
paragraph), Dave Orr just now helped me to understand what the real problem
is.  My intention was NOT to demand that the rules team change rules, I
merely demanded <g> that they DISCUSS the rules.  At least that's what I
MEANT to say.  Now I'm REALLY embarrassed. :)

-Z
