Date:         Fri, 26 Jul 1996 07:27:30 -0400
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         "<Mark T. Tomczak>" <MacPrgmr@AOL.COM>
Subject:      Bizzare Encryption Scheme

It's rising again. The evil specter of a twenty-digest long
debate.

On July 24, Foolkiller wrote:


>We do not play it that way here.  If I run a subsidiary
>fort and the Corp rezzes a BES, (assuming there is an
>agenda in the fort) then I end the run without scoring
>the Agenda.  I (for whatever reason) choose not to
>trash BES during the first run.

>The card says "This does not affect any further runs."
>If I run again immediately, BES does not affect me.  We
>take it to mean that BES does not affect any further
>runs against the SAME agenda, whether BES was trashed
>or not.  The BES does not stipulate that the card does
>not affect further runs IF trashed.

>If this is correct (Sparky?), then I would like to
>suggest that v2.0 clarify the wording in the last
>phrase to something like this:

>"This does not affect any further attempts to score
>that agenda this turn."

Anyone else?

I would say no. Note the first line:

"Runner does not score any agenda (or agendas) on a run during
which Bizarre Encryption Scheme is ACCESSED"

If you don't trash BES, you can't score the agenda until you crack
the codes at the start of your next turn (this would reperesent
running into a fort, encounterinmg a BES, taking a copy of the
agenda home, and  working on it there.). However, if you DO trash
BES, then you're not accessing it on subsequent runs that turn; you
can score the agenda normally (you run into the fort, encounter the
BES, pay the trash cost to install a decoder in the data fort, then run
later to pick up the decoded information).

Just my 3 bits,
-A.C.
