Subject:      Re: Stupider Cheaters
In-Reply-To:  <Chameleon.960725130343.bing@massive.its.bldrdoc.gov>

On Thu, 25 Jul 1996, Bill Ingram wrote:

> >   I also use dice to determine what cards I'll pull from the Corp's hand
> >during a successful run on HQ (assuming I don't have *very good* reason
> >to do otherwise).
>
> There's a lot of information you can learn from picking a specific card.
> For example, when I earn the right to draw a card, I quickly reach out
> and put my fingers near a card and then pause.  Often, if I am at an
> Agenda card, the opponent will flinch and say, "Hold it, let me mix them."
> That tells me that there is at least one "good" card in his hand.  If
> he doesn't flinch, I know I'm at a non-trashable card and select a different
> one.

   Reactions can be deceiving, but if it works for you, go for it... :)
   I see all kinds of psych games, some more devious than others. This is
a standard: when a path to HQ opens up, the Corp holds his hand out and
lets you pick after your first run. Whatever you pick, the Corp doesn't
shuffle and just keeps the hand held out, inviting you to run again and
knowing full well that you know where the card you just picked is. The
implication is obvious: "Feel free to waste your actions, there's nothing
here. Go on. Pick 'em all. In order."
   I've seen Corps do this with three cards, two of which were agenda.

   For my own part, I find Urban Renewals and Trojan Horses very
slippery... :)

- dglas ("Ooops!") <-- in a very affected voice...

