Date:         Fri, 26 Jul 1996 10:30:23 -0700
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         "Marc \"Sparky\" Schmalz" <flatline@WIZARDS.COM>
Organization: Wizards of the Coast
Subject:      Remote Facility

I've talked to R&D, and they've given me their unwritten rule for
this situation.

When a card states that you will get an extra action per turn, you
must declare when you use it.  If something trashes a Remote Facility
during the Corp's turn and the Corp has not declared that it had used
the Remote Facility's extra action, they lose it.  A smart Corporation
will probably declare each turn that the first action they take is
their bonus action.  In 'formal' play, it's not assumed.

Hope that clears things up.

--
Marc Schmalz, aka Sparky!!    flatline@castle.wizards.com
Wizards of the Coast Customer Service Team
Netrunner FAQ and Main Page  - http://www.wizards.com/Netrunner
=========================================================================
Date:         Fri, 26 Jul 1996 12:21:54 -0600
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         Skip Pickle <spickle@ILI.COM>
Subject:      Re: Social Engineering

RE>Social Engineering
Foolkiller <cwagner@CWO.COM> said:
>Here's something for everybody.  When you play Social Engineering,
>what do you do with the bits you don't put into your hand?
>Do you leave them on the table?  Pick them up with your other hand?

For this sort of thing (usually this is what we do for traces), we have
some dice handy.  Rather than using bits, we hide the dice behind our
cards and pick our amounts.  With a d6, the six is usually used to
represent zero bits.  Multiple dice will allow you to choose six or
more bits.

That way it doesn't matter what bits are in sight.  It's my
understanding that players have the right to know how many bits are
in their opponent's bit pool.

Skipper Pickle
spickle@ili.com
=========================================================================
Date:         Fri, 26 Jul 1996 11:34:15 -0600
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         Mark Norton <mnorton@REDWOOD.DN.HAC.COM>
Subject:      Re: Stupider Cheaters
In-Reply-To:  <no.id> from "Greg Dglas Teed" at Jul 26, 96 07:00:03 am

> > There's a lot of information you can learn from picking a specific card.
> > For example, when I earn the right to draw a card, I quickly reach out
> > and put my fingers near a card and then pause.  Often, if I am at an
> > Agenda card, the opponent will flinch and say, "Hold it, let me mix them."
> > That tells me that there is at least one "good" card in his hand.  If
> > he doesn't flinch, I know I'm at a non-trashable card and select a differen
> > one.

Wouldn't work for me.  Generally playing the Corp, when it's Runner's
turn, I keep my hand squared up and in the fort.  When the Runner
successfully makes a run on HQ, I pick them up flat, then shuffle them
a few times over and under, and then hold them out flat to the Runner to
pick.  I know what's in the hand of course, but don't kow the precise
card the Runner will pick.

The other thing I prefer to do is have the Runner point to a card and
have me pull it out myself and hand it to him.  I've had times when the
Runner pulled the card out of my hand and 2 or 3 other cards also fall
out due to friction and sometimes fall right side up.

Regards
Mark Norton

