Date:         Fri, 26 Jul 1996 18:55:00 -0700
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         Z <zonker@WESTWORLD.COM>
Subject:      Re: NETRUNNER-L Digest - 25 Jul 1996 to 26 Jul 1996

>Has anyone contrived a way to play this game via E-mail yet.
>Unfortunately, I'm on a freenet and don't have "Real Internet Access" so
>I can't access the IRC. Well, hey, Saskatoon isn't *that* far away from
>California.... :)
>   I'd love to take on some of elite tacticians on this list... :)

That can indeed be done, but it's so annoying that I don't participate.

There are generally three ways of doing it:

1) You just take your decks and play.  Cheating is VERY easy to do, and wins
can    be controversial.  You can essentially draw any card you need at any
time,    even if you don't own it.  Of course, this last part is a problem
no matter    which method you choose to play.

2) Two players both send the contents of their decks to each other, and
numbers    are assigned to each card.  Then, a "random" number is sent for
each card    drawn, each number corresponding to a certain card.  Again,
cheating can    easily happen, as you can choose your opponents' next card
if you want.

3) Have a third party that both players trust provide the random numbers.
This    is the best option, but you can still claim that you have 4 Roving
Subs in    your deck, even if you only own one starter deck worth of cards.

The worst part of it is the detail you must go into so that your opponent
knows exactly what your playing field looks like.  Sure, you can cut &
paste, but I still find it tedious.  Also, a single game can take weeks,
even months to play.

-Z
