Date:         Sat, 27 Jul 1996 15:45:07 +1100
Reply-To:     Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
Sender:       Netrunner Discussion List <NETRUNNER-L@ORACLE.WIZARDS.COM>
From:         Graham Hall <Graham@ZETA.ORG.AU>
Organization: Kryptonite Computing Pty Ltd
Subject:      Stuff

Question: I have been trying to put a virus deck together, and have provisionaly
included "Code Virus Cache" (Resource, 1 to install) -
"Play only if you made a successful on HQ this turn. If the corp forgoes actions to
lose virus counters, two counters of your choice are not removed. The corp may trash
viral cache by taking an action to pay 5".
I assume this means that the corp can trash CVC anytime in their turn, and that CVC
can only be "played" by the runner when the corp forgoes actions in the runner's
turn, and only after the successful HQ run?

Deck idea: I taught a friend how to play Netrunner, and during his first game as corp,
he created multiple subsidary data forts, all lightly guarded. This was contrary to my
usual strategy, which is to create a few heavily guarded forts. The interesting thing
was that it created so many choices for me as the runner, and made "see ya" or "mouse"
harder to use just because of the actions wasted (although it made "I Spy" more
attractive). Based on that game, I have created a deck with lots of cards that can be
advanced. Here's a perfect game: draw lots of ice; guard R&D, and create multiple
subsidary forts; draw more cards; start installing "experimental AI", "Vacant
soulkiller", "corprunners shattered remains", "Information laundering", "Vapor ops"
and agendas ("project babylon" especially); advance nodes and agendas each turn. Faced
with so many choices, the runner is going to have to spend all actions running and
getting potentially wasted, or using mouse/see ya. As soon as the runner uses mouse, I
install a "namatoki plaza" on a fort with "vacant soulkiller" advanced, then install
an agenda their as well, and it's locked up tighter than a very tight thing. Ideas?
Thoughts?

Opinion: I think the runner is at a disadvantage for one reason - their decks are
slower. A runner has to cater for all corp desks (tag&bag, speed, etc) which means
some cards will be useless in their deck, while a corp can tailor their deck to have
100% useful cards for the chosen theme. Mantis, short circuit etc get around this to a
degree, but they also cost actions and bits, and you're slowed down again.

Graham Hall
graham@krypton.com.au
