From:         "Brian \"SPOT\" Dorricott" <spotone@MINDPORT.NET>
Organization: SPOTone Services
Subject:      Re: Illegal tactic?

Mike Foster wrote:
>
> At 08:08 PM 7/25/96 -0400, you wrote:
>
> >Here's a tactic that the people I play with have started using:
> >
> >hide your bits.  A starter deck box works good for this, just put your
> >bit counters behind it.  The opponent quickly loses track of how many
> >bits you have, and then won't be able to know ahead of time if you can
> >rez that Mastiff/afford that run.
>
> I couldn't find it anywhere in the rules, but I'm sure this is illegal.
> Sparky? Care to make a ruling, or show us where the rule is?
> The potential for cheating with a hidden bit pool is enormous, and it takes
> quite a bit of the strategy out of the game.

Having lost my rules book I refer you to the online rules book.
at page http://www.wizards.com/Netrunner/NR_Layout_Corp.html wich shows
a picture of the corps layout it shows clearly the bitpool unhidden and
the message underneath says "HQ (our cards in our hand and our bit
pool)" I know this is about as Anal as the tap is 90 degrees fight we
had in M:TOG but the fact is that the bit pool is an area that is freely
inspectable by both sides at anytime the trash and archives(face up) are
also that way. the runners bit pool is also seen in
http://www.wizards.com/Netrunner/NR_Layout_Runner.html although no
mention is given that it is to be associated with anything.
I repeat it may seem Anal but the fact is it is neccesary to prevent
cheating.
